<module>
  <title>anthroponymic proper nouns</title>
  <p>Anthroponymic proper nouns are <a href="?xx=nouns/proper_nouns">proper nouns</a> which are also <a href="?xx=nouns/anthroponyms">anthroponyms</a>, 
    i.e. they name people (and other personified entities like toys, boats, houses, pet animals, &amp;c).</p>
  <p>Feminine anthroponymic proper nouns name female persons, <m>Mairead</m>
    <en>Margaret</en>, <m>Caitrìona</m>
    <en>Catherine</en>. They are slenderised, but not (necessarily) lenited, in both the dative and genitive cases, e.g. <m>le Maireid</m>
    <en>with Margaret</en>, <m>taigh Maireid</m>
    <en>Margaret’s house</en>. <boxlink ref="#feminine_anthroponyms"/></p>
  <box id="feminine_anthroponyms">
    <title>feminine anthroponymic proper nouns</title>
    <p>Feminine anthroponymic proper nouns name female persons. They are slenderised, but not (necessarily) lenited, in both the dative and genitive cases –</p>
    <table class="table w-auto">
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <th>nominative</th>
          <td><m>Mairead</m></td>
          <td><m>Sìne</m></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>dative</th>
          <td>(le) Maireid</td>
          <td>(le) Sìne</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>genitive</th>
          <td>(taigh) Maireid</td>
          <td>(taigh) Sìne</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>Note that feminine anthroponymic proper nouns ending with a vowel or slender consonant show no change in the dative or genitive.</p>
    <p>Note also that genitive forms of feminine anthroponymic proper nouns are systematically lenited in some dialects, cf. ?<i>taigh Mhaireid</i>.</p>
