  <p>Anthroponymic proper nouns maybe be juxtaposed with, modified or specified by other words as follows –</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Two anthroponymic proper nouns may be juxtaposed in apposition (i.e. agreeing in gender and case), e.g. <m>Màiri Sìne</m>
      <en>Mary Jane</en>, <m>Dòmhnall Uilleam</m>
      <en>Donald William</en>. <boxlink ref="#double-barrelled_names"/></li>
    <li>An anthroponymic proper noun may be modified by a following adjective, agreeing in both gender and case, e.g. <m>Mairead Bhàn</m>
      <en>Fair Margaret</en>, <m>Seumas Mòr</m>
      <en>Big James</en>. <boxlink ref="#anthroponymic_adjectives"/></li>
    <li>An anthroponymic proper noun (usually masculine) may be followed, in apposition, by a simple common noun denoting a job or profession, e.g. <m>Dòmhnall Breabadair</m>
      <en>Donald the Weaver</en>
      <boxlink ref="#anthroponymic_jobs"/></li>
    <li>More apposition – Seumas mac Dhòmhnaill, Mairead nighean a’ Mhinisteir, Màiri bean Sheumais. And: Seumas mac Dhòmhnaill mhic Sheumais, Iain fear Chanaidh</li>
    <li>An anthroponymic proper noun may be specified by a following common noun or proper noun. Seumas a’ Bhreabadair. Seumas Dhòmhnaill (Sheumais). Iain Chanaidh.</li>
  </ol>
  <box id="double-barrelled_names">
    <title>‘double-barrelling’ of anthroponymic proper nouns</title>
    <p>Two anthroponymic proper nouns may be combined in apposition to form a ‘double-barrelled’ personal name, e.g. <m>Màiri Sìne</m>
      <en>Mary Jane</en>, <m>Dòmhnall Uilleam</m>
      <en>Donald William</en>.</p>
    <p>Since the two nouns are in apposition, they agree in both gender and case –</p>
    <table class="table w-auto">
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <th>nominative</th>
          <td><m>Mòr Màiread</m></td>
          <td><m>Dòmhnall Seumas</m></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>dative</th>
          <td>(le) Mòir Màireid</td>
          <td>(le) Dòmhnall Seumas</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>genitive</th>
          <td>(taigh) Mòir Màireid</td>
          <td>(taigh) Dhòmhnaill Sheumais</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>Note the following vocative examples from Cox (2017: 125) with regard to lenition of the second noun – <m>A Thormoid C<u>h</u>aluim!</m>
      <m>A Mhàiri Sìne!</m></p>
  </box>
  <box id="anthroponymic_adjectives">
    <title>anthroponymic proper nouns modified by adjectives</title>
    <p>An anthroponymic proper noun may be modified by one or more following adjectives, e.g. <m>Mairead Bhàn</m>
      <en>Fair Margaret</en>, <m>Dòmhnall Beag Ruadh</m>
      <en>Little Red Donald</en>.</p>
    <p>The adjectives agree with the proper noun in both gender and case –</p>
    <table class="table w-auto">
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <th>nominative</th>
          <td><m>Màiread Dhonn</m></td>
          <td><m>Dòmhnall Beag Ruadh</m></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>dative</th>
          <td>(le) Màireid Dhuinn</td>
          <td>(le) Dòmhnall Beag Ruadh</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>genitive</th>
          <td>(taigh) Màireid Duinne</td>
          <td>(taigh) Dhòmhnaill Bhig Ruaidh</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </box>
  <box id="anthroponymic_jobs">
    <title>anthroponymic proper nouns with nouns denoting jobs</title>
